Mar 2023
Just spent 5 days in Monti and it is an excellent starting point to walk to many of Rome’s major attractions while being immersed in a local neighborhood. 5 minutes from Cavour metro/subway station. Plenty of excellent restaurants from higher end Osteria Al 16 to Trieste Pizza with delicious pizza by a humerus and engaging chef. My wife, 12 year old daughter and mom enjoyed eating gelato in the Fontana dei Catecumeni.

Mairwen1
United Kingdom11,518 contributions
Exploring the Monti Area...
Jun 2022
You can easily spend a couple of hours exploring the Rione Monti area. We found it very easy to walk around the main sights and it’s only minutes from the Colosseum. When you read up on Monti, the descriptions use words like ‘bohemian’ and ‘hipster hotspot’. It certainly has an appealing mix of artisan and vintage shops, churches, restaurants and bars which sit alongside the ancient ruins of Trajan’s market and treasures like Michelangelo’s ‘Moses’.
We came here specifically to see Michelangelo’s Moses in the Basilica di San Pietro in Vincoli. It was tricky to find and we got a little lost until we back-tracked and found the big flight of stairs on via Cavour. The basilica was at the very top of the stairs. Inside, the colossal marble statue is amazing and even more amazingly, the basilica was relatively empty so we could stand and linger in front of it, uninterrupted (entry is free).
Another fun discovery was the small Vespa Museum on Via Cavour. The window display of cleverly decorated Vespas caught our eye. It's actually a bike & Vespa shop, Bici e Baci, with a small museum downstairs. Entry is free.
There are lots of places to stop for a drink or meal. We had a good lunch at Gli Angeletti and finished our Monti explorations in the Piazza della Madonna dei Monti with an Aperol Spritz where people were perched with drinks around the steps of the central fountain.
Written June 7, 2022
